solution.p:
We can write 105\degree as the sum of two special angles: 105\degree = 60\degree + 45\degree. Now apply the sum of angles identity for cosine.
\cos (60\degree + 45\degree) \amp = \cos 60\degree \cos 45\degree - \sin 60\degree \sin 45\degree \amp = \dfrac{1}{2} \dfrac{\sqrt{2}}{2}-\dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \dfrac{\sqrt{2}}{2} = \dfrac{\sqrt{2}-\sqrt{6}}{4}
Thus, \cos 105\degree = \dfrac{\sqrt{2}-\sqrt{6}}{4}. You can check that your calculator gives the same decimal approximation of about -0.2588 for both \cos 105\degree and \dfrac{\sqrt{2}-\sqrt{6}}{4}.

Recall that \sin \dfrac{2\pi}{3} = \dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2} and \cos \dfrac{2\pi}{3} = \dfrac{-1}{2}.  Substituting these values into the sum formula for sine, we find

		\sin(\theta + \dfrac{2\pi}{3}) \amp = \sin \theta \cos \dfrac{2\pi}{3} +\cos \theta	\sin \dfrac{2\pi}{3}
		\amp = 0.6 \left(\dfrac{-1}{2}\right) +(-0.8)\left(\dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\right)
		\amp = \dfrac{3}{5} \cdot \dfrac{-1}{2} + \dfrac{-4}{5} \cdot \dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2} = \dfrac{-3-4\sqrt{3}}{10}

