solution.p:
Remember that \cos \dfrac{\pi}{4} = \dfrac{\sqrt{2}}{2},~~\cos\dfrac{\pi}{6} =\dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2},~~\sin\dfrac{\pi}{4} = \dfrac{\sqrt{2}}{2}, and \sin \dfrac{\pi}{6} = \dfrac{1}{2}. Substituting all these values into the difference formula for cosine, we obtain the following.

		\cos\dfrac{\pi}{12} \amp = \cos (\dfrac{\pi}{4} - \dfrac{\pi}{6})
		\amp = \cos \dfrac{\pi}{4} \cos \dfrac{\pi}{6} + \sin \dfrac{\pi}{4} \sin \dfrac{\pi}{6}
		amp = \dfrac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \cdot \dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2} +\dfrac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \cdot \dfrac{1}{2}
		\amp = \dfrac{\sqrt{6}+\sqrt{2}}{4}

You can check that your calculator gives the same decimal approximation of about 0.9659 for both \cos \dfrac{\pi}{12} and \dfrac{\sqrt{6}+\sqrt{2}}{4}.

We observe that 75\degree = 45\degree + 30\degree, so \tan 75\degree = \tan (45\degree + 30\degree).  We can apply the sum formula for tangent.

		\tan(45\degree + 30\degree) \amp = \dfrac{\tan 45\degree + \tan 30\degree}{1 - \tan 45\degree \tan 30\degree}
		\amp = \dfrac{1+\dfrac{1}{\sqrt{3}}}{1-1(\dfrac{1}{\sqrt{3}})} \cdot \blert{\dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{\sqrt{3}}} =\dfrac{\sqrt{3}+1}{\sqrt{3}-1}

warning.p:
The first thing we can learn from the double angle formulas is that \sin 2	heta is not equal to 2\sin 	heta! You can check this very easily by choosing a value for 	heta, say 45\degree. Then
\sin 2	heta \amp = \sin (90\degree) =1 	ext{but}~~~ 2\sin 	heta\amp = 2\sin (45\degree) = 2(\dfrac{\sqrt{2}}{2}) = \sqrt{2}
and \sqrt{2} 
ot= 1. Similarly, \cos 2	heta 
ot= 2\cos 	heta and 	an 2	heta 
ot= 2	an 	heta

